english:
  title: Preface to Poems Sent Off to Master Youyun of the Huayan School
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Youyun of the Huayan school is the son of Chamberlain Jinggong, known as Zhuoxuan, and younger brother to Chamberlain Gong, known as Xizhai. In his youth, he devoted himself to the Huayan order, took monastic vows, and studied the teachings of the Xianshou school until his learning became complete. He crossed the Yalu River, traveled through Liaodong and Shenyang, journeyed north to the capital of Yan, and then wandered south through Jiangsu and Zhejiang, reaching the lands of Wu. Over his travels of thousands upon thousands of li, everywhere he went, the venerable masters acknowledged him, his peers held him in esteem, and they left him with gathas and parting verses that filled his satchel. Was this not the spirit of Sudhana the seeker, awakened in his heart?

    When he returned eastward, he and his younger brother, Master Canji of the Cao River lineage, both became renowned. They were greatly favored by the king. He lived in various great temples, and in his later years withdrew to the Danan Hermitage in Gyeongju, spending five or six years at leisure among mountains and streams. The state compelled him to return as abbot of the Furen Temple on Bagong Mountain—truly a great monastery. Soon after, he was summoned to the Fawang Temple in Song-kyung, appointed as Master of the Huayan school, to uphold the tradition and enlighten later students. Yet after scarcely a year, his desire to depart grew so pressing that the state, left with no choice, granted his request. Master Mokeun of Hansan first composed poems in his honor, and many others followed with their verses. His disciple Yizhen came bearing his master's request for a preface. I, Dao-chuan, am unworthy—what can I say? Yet the Kim family are descendants of the great clans of the Three Han kingdoms, and have long made poetry, books, ritual, and music the teachings of their household. Thus Master Youyun's cultivation has deep roots. Now, Huayan fuses with the Dharma-character school into one body, penetrating the truth that principle and phenomena are not two. His learning is vast indeed. Having traveled widely through the lands and observed mountains and rivers, having encountered many people, what he has gained from such observation and experience runs deep. With these three things, wherever can he go without finding himself? Yet the Master remains serene in compliance, calm in his return, unattached and desiring nothing of the world. His conduct is truly lofty. Thus it is fitting that when he withdraws, others advance, and when he departs, others remember him. This is why the gentlemen have composed these poems in his honor. And I too dare make this my preface.
  footnotes:
    - Sudhana (善財) refers to the young pilgrim in the Huayan sutra who seeks wisdom through extensive travels and encounters with enlightened masters—a biographical parallel to Master Youyun's own journey.
    - 'The ''three things'' refer to: (1) cultivation rooted in family tradition of learning and ritual propriety, (2) profound understanding of Buddhist philosophy, and (3) deep insight gained through extensive travels and observation of the world.'
